21 the assessment plat; and (2) if written remonstrances by the owners of tracts
22 constituting one-third or more of the basis for the computation of assessments for
23 the neighborhood improvement project are presented to the governing body, the
24 governing body is prohibited from proceeding with the project. (NRS 271.305,
25 271.306) Section 3 of this bill provides that this prohibition does not apply to a
26 neighborhood improvement project that improves a water or sewer system that is
27 owned by a common-interest community. Instead, section 4 of this bill provides
28 that a neighborhood improvement project that improves a water or sewer system
29 that is owned by a common-interest community will not be stayed or defeated or
30 prevented by written complaints, protests and objections, unless the governing body
31 deems such written complaints, protests and objections proper to cause the
32 neighborhood improvement project to be stayed or prevented.
33 Section 5 of this bill makes a conforming change to authorize the governing
34 body of a county, city or town to proceed with the improvement district after the
35 hearing and after the governing body makes certain determinations, including a
36 determination that an exception applies that authorizes the governing body to
37 acquire or improve an improvement project despite certain complaints, protests and
38 objections.
39 Existing law requires a governing body which has acquired or improved a
40 neighborhood improvement project to annually: (1) prepare an amendment to the
41 assessment roll for the district and an estimate of the expenditures for the next
42 fiscal year; (2) hold a public meeting to consider the amendment; and (3) provide
43 certain notice to the owner of each tract being assessed. (NRS 271.377) Section 6
44 of this bill makes these provisions inapplicable to a neighborhood improvement
45 project that improves a water or sewer system that is owned by a common-interest
46 community.
